  "prompt": "Do Go-Back-N ARQ and Selective Repeat ARQ use cumulative acknowledgements or an acknowledgement for every individual packet?",
  "response": "Go-Back-N ARQ and Selective Repeat ARQ both use cumulative acknowledgments, but they do so in different contexts.\n\n1. **Go-Back-N ARQ**: In this protocol, the sender can transmit multiple frames before needing an acknowledgment for the first one, but it requires the receiver to send a cumulative acknowledgment indicating the last correctly received frame. If a frame is lost or arrives out of order, the receiver will discard that frame and all subsequent frames, prompting the sender to retransmit all frames starting from the last acknowledged frame. Thus, the acknowledgment in Go-Back-N is cumulative.\n\n2. **Selective Repeat ARQ**: Like Go-Back-N, Selective Repeat ARQ also uses cumulative acknowledgments. However, it allows the receiver to accept out-of-order frames. It will send acknowledgments for each individual frame that it successfully receives, which can be considered as a form of cumulative acknowledgment, as it indicates which frames have been received successfully. Meanwhile, the sender only retransmits the specific frames that were not acknowledged or were received incorrectly.\n\nIn summary, both protocols utilize cumulative acknowledgments but have different ways of managing the acknowledgment process: Go-Back-N is more conservative, while Selective Repeat allows for more flexibility with out-of-order frames and individual acknowledgments.",
